<doc id="627828" wikidata="Q1318413" url="?curid=627828" title="Double Mersenne number">
<text>In mathematics, a double Mersenne number is a Mersenne number of the form

:formula_1

where &quot;p&quot; is prime.

== Examples ==
The first four terms of the sequence of double Mersenne numbers are :
:formula_2
:formula_3
:formula_4
:formula_5

== Double Mersenne primes ==
A double Mersenne number that is prime is called a double Mersenne prime. Since a Mersenne number &quot;M&quot;&quot;p&quot; can be prime only if &quot;p&quot; is prime, (see Mersenne prime for a proof), a double Mersenne number formula_6 can be prime only if &quot;M&quot;&quot;p&quot; is itself a Mersenne prime. For the first values of &quot;p&quot; for which &quot;M&quot;&quot;p&quot; is prime, formula_7 is known to be prime for &quot;p&quot; = 2, 3, 5, 7 while explicit factors of formula_7 have been found for &quot;p&quot; = 13, 17, 19, and 31.

Thus, the smallest candidate for the next double Mersenne prime is formula_9, or 22305843009213693951 − 1.
Being approximately 1.695,
this number is far too large for any currently known primality test. It has no prime factor below 1 × 1036.
There are probably no other double Mersenne primes than the four known.

Smallest prime factor of formula_7 (where &quot;p&quot; is the &quot;n&quot;th prime) are

:7, 127, 2147483647, 170141183460469231731687303715884105727, 47, 338193759479, 231733529, 62914441, 2351, 1399, 295257526626031, 18287, 106937, 863, 4703, 138863, 22590223644617, ... (next term is &gt; 1 × 1036) 

==Catalan–Mersenne number conjecture==

The recursively defined sequence
: formula_11
: formula_12
is called the sequence of Catalan–Mersenne numbers. The first terms of the sequence are: 
:formula_13
:formula_14
:formula_15
:formula_16
:formula_17
:formula_18
Catalan discovered this sequence after the discovery of the primality of formula_19 by Lucas in 1876. Catalan conjectured that they are prime &quot;up to a certain limit&quot;. Although the first five terms are prime, no known methods can prove that any further terms are prime (in any reasonable time) simply because they are too huge. However, if formula_20 is not prime, there is a chance to discover this by computing formula_20 modulo some small prime formula_22 (using recursive modular exponentiation). If the resulting residue is zero, formula_22 represents a factor of formula_20 and thus would disprove its primality. Since formula_20 is a Mersenne number, such a prime factor formula_22 would have to be of the form formula_27. Additionally, because formula_28 is composite when formula_29 is composite, the discovery of a composite term in the sequence would preclude the possibility of any further primes in the sequence.

If formula_20 were prime, it would also contradict the New Mersenne conjecture. It is known that formula_31 is composite, with factor formula_32.

==In popular culture==
In the Futurama movie , the double Mersenne number formula_33 is briefly seen in &quot;an elementary proof of the Goldbach conjecture&quot;. In the movie, this number is known as a &quot;Martian prime&quot;.

